name: Be a Fisherman by Artifishal
description:
In Be a Fisherman, Artifishal invites viewers into a cosmic dreamscape where the boundaries between self, identity, and the universe dissolve into starlight and shadow. The title suggests a narrative tied to fishing—perhaps the ancient metaphor of seeking and discovery—but intriguingly, there’s not a single fish in sight. That absence isn’t a flaw; it’s a deliberate sleight of hand. Fishing, in Artifishal’s world, is not about the catch—it’s about the search itself.

What sets Be a Fisherman apart is how it translated this existential search into the mechanics of collecting. Rather than offering a fixed print edition to mint, Artifishal invited collectors to engage with the work through a minting mechanism based on chance and risk. 49 print editions of each of the 11 works were released, with a single original of each work interspersed among them, creating a total of 550 pieces.

name: Behold by Steven Miller x Metablend Studios
description:
BEHOLD is an engaging exploration of Perception, Subjectivity, and Connection.

At first glance, each of the collection's 508 Independently Curated Generative Artworks evoke a sense of familiarity and piques our inquisitive nature… but in a flash, that singular moment of shared curiosity gives way to a broad spectrum of personal backstories and individual experiences. On one hand, a bright-eyed observer might relate the composition and form to the intricacy of the human eye. While on the other, an Art Historian might liken the instinctive rush of wonder and the strikingly surreal, untethered void to the hallmarks of Romanticism, Liminalism and Geometric Abstraction. 

These two radically different perspectives view the work with varying levels of nuance, education, and experience — yet both are equally justified. After all, it’s only by recognizing both our shared experiences and our differences that we come to refine how we interpret and understand the beauty within any work of art.

The last copper pennies were minted in 1982, after which they have been struck in zinc. A penny from any given year will always be worth exactly 1¢, according to the US Treasury, but the copper in pre-1982 pennies has a metal value of approximately 3¢. Recognizing these discrepancies in value, Rutherford Chang removed 10,000 copper coins from circulation and archivally documented them. The final state of these 10,000 copper cents are inscribed on 10,000 satoshis, while the physical coins are smelted and cast into a solid 68-pound copper block. This metal block is rendered as a three-dimensional digital model and inscribed as a 4-megabyte ordinal, comprising the entirety of Bitcoin block #839969. As the traditional penny fades into irrelevance and its production is ultimately terminated, its value can continue to be redefined. rutherfordchang.com/cents

description:
YAKUYOKE is a photo-based glitch/generative art work.

- YAKU (厄): misfortune or calamity
- YOKE (除け): to ward off or get rid of.

It is a ceremony held at Japanese shrines to shake off bad luck and misfortune and wish for good fortune. 

The theme of the project was this: "Can I express the flame to ward off misfortune and calamity?"

The act of burning eight pure street photographs taken in Shibuya, Tokyo, and making them non-transferable corresponds to the act of burning firewood. 

Using p5.js and WEBGL programs, the Burned photo data is randomly retrieved by Recursion, and various glitch destructions are added to reproduce the flames of burning bad luck. 

All eight photographic inscriptions are Burned, making them non-transferable and non-sellable. The generative art program is inscribe on Uncommon Sats. Programs and photos are in a Parent-Child provenance.
